{"cursor":"3748","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox person |name =Makoto Kano |imagesize =100px |caption ='Nintendo\nCompany Limited R&D1' |employer =Nintendo (1974â ) |birth_date = |birth_place\n=Kyoto, Japan |occupation =Nintendo Supervisor Game Designer |website\n=[http://www.nintendo.co.jp www.nintendo.co.jp] }}\n\n, also credited as 'Makoto Kanoh' pre-1995, is a Japanese\ngame designer and supervisor. He was born in Kyoto, Japan.\n\nKano began working for Nintendo in 1974. He was one of the original designers in\nNintendo's creative department. Originally, he designed toys and board games\nbefore working on the Nintendo Beam Gun series. Kano eventually became one of\nthe lead designers of the [[Game & Watch]] series. By 1984, he was heavily\ninvolved in several Nintendo R&D1 games, including [[Hogan's Alley (video\ngame)|Hogan's Alley]], [[Gyromite]], and more specifically the [[Metroid (video\ngame)|Metroid]], [[Kid Icarus]], and [[Famicom Wars]] series. Some other\nprojects he has worked on at Nintendo include [[Super Metroid]], the Super Scope\nfor the Super Nintendo Entertainment System, and [[Mario & Wario]].\n\nKano is credited with creating several early Nintendo characters during the\n1980s. Ultimately, his best known achievement may have been creating the\nconcepts of the Metroid, Famicom Wars, and Kid Icarus universe. [http://themushroomkingdom.net/ssbm_credits-\nfull.shtml Makoto Kano - Creator of Several Nintendo Characters ][http://www.nintendo.co.jp/n10/interview/game_and_watch/vol1/index-\n.html Iwata Asks: Game & Watch ]\n","linknr":136,"url":"Makoto_Kano_(video_game_designer)","recorded":1374780309,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Makoto_Kano_(video_game_designer)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Makoto_Kano_(video_game_designer)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Speci